	<text>
		<body>
				<p><add>&#63;</add>evening with the sons of <persName>Mr Sassan</persName>&#44; the rich Jewish banker of<lb/> <placeName>Bombay</placeName>.  I stated there the same facts&#44; I am herewith presenting<lb/> to the reader&#44; and <del>the Chief Rabbi</del> <persName>Dr. Stern</persName> examining the Young <persName>Sassons</persName>&#44; regar<lb/>ding the truth of my statements&#44; they emphatically asserted&#44; that<lb/> they could testify to his statement&#44; as well as to the ingenuity of<lb/> my book.  This assertion on the part of so highly respectable<lb/> witnesses refutes <del>not only the alleged slander&#44; but also</del> the statement<lb/> of the criticism&#44; that I had compiled a book&#44; without having wit&#45;<lb/>nessed these distant regions.</p>
				<p>Thus the points raised by <del>Rev</del> <persName>Mr Gutheim</persName> against me&#44; are open&#45;<lb/>ly and frankly <del>laid</del> refuted as willful <del>and malicious</del> misrepresen&#45;<lb/>tations&#44; and I have only to add&#44; why <del>the Rev Rabbi of New&#45;Or&#758;</del><lb/><del>leans at once has</del> he became so deadly hostile against me <add>after his first friendly recept.</add>&#44; and<lb/> insisted upon the reconsideration <add>of the vote</add> passed by the Heb. Foreign Messers<lb/> in my favour.</p>
				<p><del>The Rev gentleman</del> <persName>Mr G.</persName>&#44; namely&#44; proposed to his congregation&#44; to erect<lb/> a monument to the late <persName>Judah Touro</persName> in front of the new Portu&#758;<lb/>guese Synagogue.  According to the <hi rend="underline">Shulchan&#45;Aruch&#44; Joreh&#45;Deah</hi><lb/> I objected to his proposition&#44; and published several articles against<lb/> his innovation.  This step of mine excited the ire of the Rev. gentle&#758;<lb/>man&#44; that disregarding all justice and impartiality&#44; and considering<lb/> only the merits or demerits of the case under consideration&#44; he<lb/> <sic>recurrs</sic> to <del>slander and</del> calumny&#44; in order to injure my cause and<lb/> reputation&#44; and to weaken the objections&#44; I had raised against<lb/> his favorite scheme.</p>
				<p>These&#44; Mr Editor&#44; are the plain and stubborn matters of fact.  Let the<lb/> public now judge between me and <del>the Rev. Gentleman</del> him&#44; and let them decide&#44;<lb/> whether I have a right&#44; to decry his <add>&#63;</add> article as a <del>wilful</del><lb/> <del>and malicious slander&#33;</del> totally unfounded</p>
				<p>Hoping&#44; that you will insert into your valuable paper this article<lb/> of defense&#44; as you have published  the article from <placeName>New Orleans</placeName><lb/> I remain</p>
				<p><add>&#63;</add> <persName role="author">Benjamin II</persName></p>
				<p>Note As a matter of justice in point <persName role="author">Mr. Benjamin&#39;s</persName> reply&#59; but in<lb/> <add>&#63;</add> that <persName>Mr Gutheim</persName> would be a <add>&#63;</add> by such b<add>&#63;</add><lb/> notion is <persName role="author">Mr B.</persName> alleges to have you round his corner.  We fear that <add>&#63;</add> above<lb/> will not satisfy the public more than it has ourself.</p>
